itical (Must Fix)\\n    15→\\n    16→1. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:211] Unbounded `io.ReadAll` on stdin in `ParseHookEvent`**\\n    17→\\n    18→   `ParseHookEvent` calls `io.ReadAll(stdin)` without any size limit. Since external plugins receive data from agent hooks (which may include arbitrary payloads), a malformed or malicious input stream could cause OOM. This is especially important because `ParseHookEvent` is called during git hook execution, where the CLI acts as a gatekeeper.\\n    19→\\n    20→   Suggested fix: Use `io.LimitReader(stdin, maxParseHookBytes)` with a reasonable limit (e.g., 10MB).\\n    21→\\n    22→   ```go\\n    23→   const maxParseHookBytes = 10 * 1024 * 1024\\n    24→   data, err := io.ReadAll(io.LimitReader(stdin, maxParseHookBytes))\\n    25→   ```\\n    26→\\n    27→2. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:97-98] `ReadTranscript` passes `sessionRef` as a CLI argument without validation**\\n    28→\\n    29→   The `sessionRef` value originates from session metadata and is passed as `--session-ref` to the external binary. In the test agent (`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire-agent-test/main.go`:167), this is used directly as a file path in `os.ReadFile(*sessionRef)`. While the CLI itself is not performing the file read, it is passing potentially attacker-controlled strings to an external process as arguments.\\n    30→\\n    31→   This is less of a concern than it might appear because:\\n    32→   - The external binary is trusted (found on PATH, user opted in via `external_agents: true`)\\n    33→   - The CLI is not interpreting the value, just forwarding it\\n    34→\\n    35→   However, the `sessionRef` and similar path parameters (`--path`, `--session-dir`, `--subagents-dir`) are passed as CLI arguments that could contain shell metacharacters. Since `exec.CommandContext` does NOT invoke a shell, this is safe from shell injection. **No action required** -- documenting this for the record.\\n    36→\\n    37→### Important (Should Fix)\\n    38→\\n    39→3. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:97-98, 118, 128, 140, 152, 169, 193, 272, 284, 297, 310, 334, 363, 373, 386] Many methods use `context.Background()` instead of accepting a context parameter**\\n    40→\\n    41→   Fifteen methods create a fresh `context.Background()` instead of propagating a caller-supplied context. This means:\\n    42→   - The 30-second default timeout from `run()` is the only safeguard\\n    43→   - Callers cannot cancel these operations (e.g., during graceful shutdown)\\n    44→   - Operations triggered during git hooks (which have tight time budgets) cannot enforce their own deadlines\\n    45→\\n    46→   The `agent.Agent` interface methods like `ReadTranscript`, `GetSessionID`, `ResolveSessionFile`, `FormatResumeCommand`, etc. do not accept a context, so fixing this would require interface changes. At minimum, consider:\\n    47→   - Filing a follow-up issue to add context to the agent interface\\n    48→   - Adding a comment explaining why `context.Background()` is used (interface limitation)\\n    49→\\n    50→4. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/hooks_cmd.go`:31-32] Discovery timeout context is cancelled immediately after `DiscoverAndRegister` returns, but the context was already used synchronously**\\n    51→\\n    52→   The code is:\\n    53→   ```go\\n    54→   discoveryCtx, discoveryCancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 5*time.Second)\\n    55→   defer discoveryCancel()\\n    56→   external.DiscoverAndRegister(discoveryCtx)\\n    57→   ```\\n    58→\\n    59→   The `defer discoveryCancel()` fires when `newHooksCmd()` returns. Since `DiscoverAndRegister` is synchronous, this works correctly. However, there is a subtle issue: the 5-second timeout is for ALL discovery combined. If there are many `entire-agent-*` binaries on PATH, each `New()` call gets a share of this budget, but a single slow binary could consume most of it, starving later ones. The `New()` call inherits the discovery context deadline, so slow binaries will eventually timeout, but the remaining budget for subsequent binaries shrinks.\\n    60→\\n    61→   This is acceptable for now but worth documenting. Consider logging the remaining budget when starting each binary probe during discovery.\\n    62→\\n    63→5. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/discovery.go`:55-56] Agent name from filename is used without sanitization**\\n    64→\\n    65→   The agent name is derived from the binary filename:\\n    66→   ```go\\n    67→   agentName := types.AgentName(strings.TrimPrefix(name, binaryPrefix))\\n    68→   ```\\n    69→\\n    70→   If a binary is named `entire-agent-../../etc/shadow`, the resulting agent name would be `../../etc/shadow`. While this does not cause path traversal (the name is used as a registry key, not a file path), it could cause confusion in logs and display. Consider validating the agent name contains only `[a-z0-9-]` characters.\\n    71→\\n    72→   Suggested fix:\\n    73→   ```go\\n    74→   agentName := strings.TrimPrefix(name, binaryPrefix)\\n    75→   if !regexp.MustCompile(`^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9-]*$`).MatchString(agentName) {\\n    76→       logging.Debug(ctx, \\\"skipping external agent (invalid name)\\\", slog.String(\\\"binary\\\", name))\\n    77→       continue\\n    78→   }\\n    79→   ```\\n    80→\\n    81→6. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:415-416] `cmd.Environ()` inherits the full parent environment**\\n    82→\\n    83→   The external binary receives the entire environment of the CLI process. This includes potentially sensitive variables (API keys, tokens, etc.). Consider using a minimal environment instead, or at least documenting this as a security consideration in the protocol docs.\\n    84→\\n    85→   At minimum, the protocol documentation should state that external agents receive the parent process environment, so plugin authors are aware they should not leak env vars.\\n    86→\\n    87→7. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:427] No limit on stdout buffer size**\\n    88→\\n    89→   `cmd.Stdout = &stdoutBuf` collects the entire stdout of the external binary into memory. A malicious or buggy external agent could write gigabytes to stdout, causing OOM. Consider wrapping the buffer with a `LimitedWriter` or checking the size after the process exits.\\n    90→\\n    91→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n    92→\\n    93→8. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external_test.go`:36-101] Test mock scripts use shell string interpolation for JSON**\\n    94→\\n    95→   The `mockInfoScript` function builds shell scripts by string-concatenating JSON:\\n    96→   ```go\\n    97→   return `#!/bin/sh\\n    98→   case \\\"$1\\\" in\\n    99→     info)\\n   100→       echo '` + infoJSON + `'\\n   101→   ```\\n   102→\\n   103→   If `infoJSON` contains single quotes, this will break the shell script. The current tests are safe because the JSON values are controlled, but this is fragile. Consider using a heredoc or writing the JSON to a separate file that the script reads.\\n   104→\\n   105→9. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/capabilities.go`] `wrappedAgent` duplicates every method signature from `Agent`**\\n   106→\\n   107→   The `wrappedAgent` is a thin delegation layer with ~80 lines of boilerplate. This is a reasonable approach in Go (no built-in delegation), but consider adding a comment at the top of the struct explaining why all methods are forwarded rather than using embedding (embedding would expose the underlying `*Agent` directly and bypass capability gating).\\n   108→\\n   109→10. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/discovery.go`:22-93] `DiscoverAndRegister` has no way to report partial failures to callers**\\n   110→\\n   111→    All errors during discovery are logged and swallowed. The function returns nothing. This is fine for the current fire-and-forget usage, but if callers ever need to know which agents failed and why (e.g., for `entire status` diagnostics), the function signature would need to change.\\n   112→\\n   113→    Consider returning a `[]DiscoveryError` or similar for future extensibility, even if current callers ignore it.\\n   114→\\n   115→11. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/types.go`:148-172] `eventJSON.toEvent()` uses unchecked integer cast for `EventType`**\\n   116→\\n   117→    ```go\\n   118→    ev := &agent.Event{\\n   119→        Type: agent.EventType(ej.Type),\\n   120→    ```\\n   121→\\n   122→    The `ej.Type` integer is directly cast to `agent.EventType` without validating it is a known event type. An external agent returning an unknown event type (e.g., `999`) would propagate through the system. Consider validating the type against known values.\\n   123→\\n   124→12. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:123-137] `GetSessionID` silently returns empty string on any error**\\n   125→\\n   126→    Three different error paths (marshal, run, unmarshal) all return `\\\"\\\"`. This matches the interface contract (built-in agents also return `\\\"\\\"` on failure), but makes debugging difficult. Consider adding debug logging for these failures:\\n   127→\\n   128→    ```go\\n   129→    func (e *Agent) GetSessionID(input *agent.HookInput) string {\\n   130→        data, err := marshalHookInput(input)\\n   131→        if err != nil {\\n   132→            logging.Debug(context.Background(), \\\"GetSessionID marshal failed\\\", slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()))\\n   133→            return \\\"\\\"\\n   134→        }\\n   135→        // ...\\n   136→    }\\n   137→    ```\\n   138→\\n   139→13. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/hooks_cmd.go`:31-33] Discovery runs on every `entire hooks` invocation**\\n   140→\\n   141→    `DiscoverAndRegister` scans PATH and calls `info` on every matching binary, which happens on every git hook invocation (commit, push, etc.). This adds latency to every git operation. The 5-second timeout bounds worst case, but even the happy path involves filesystem scanning + process spawning for each plugin.\\n   142→\\n   143→    Consider caching discovery results (e.g., in a temp file with a short TTL) to avoid re-scanning on every hook call. This is especially important because git hooks are latency-sensitive.\\n   144→\\n   145→### Praise\\n   146→\\n   147→- **Capability gating pattern (`capabilities.go`)**: The `CapabilityDeclarer` + `As*` helper pattern is elegant. It allows external agents to implement all interfaces (through the `wrappedAgent`) while only exposing declared capabilities, AND it preserves backward compatibility with built-in agents that use direct type assertions. This is a well-thought-out design.\\n   148→\\n   149→- **Thorough test coverage**: The test suite covers happy paths, error cases, deduplication, name conflicts, non-executable files, directories, disabled settings, empty PATH, unreadable directories, and info failures. The capability gating tests cover all combinations of declared/undeclared capabilities for every optional interface.\\n   150→\\n   151→- **Security-conscious defaults**: The feature flag (`external_agents: false` by default), the 5-second discovery timeout, the 30-second per-call timeout, and the `WaitDelay` on subprocesses all show good defensive thinking.\\n   152→\\n   153→- **Clean refactoring**: The migration from direct type assertions (`ag.(agent.HookSupport)`) to the capability-aware helpers (`agent.AsHookSupport(ag)`) across the codebase is thorough and consistent, touching all 15+ call sites without missing any.\\n   154→\\n   155→- **Protocol versioning**: Including `protocol_version` in the `info` response and checking it upfront prevents subtle compatibility issues as the protocol evolves.\\n   156→\\n   157→## Summary\\n   158→\\n   159→**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n   160→\\n   161→The architecture is sound and the implementation is well-structured. The capability gating pattern is particularly nice. However, there are security concerns that should be addressed before merging since this feature executes untrusted external binaries:\\n   162→\\n   163→**Key concerns:**\\n   164→1. Unbounded `io.ReadAll` in `ParseHookEvent` (item 1) -- a straightforward fix\\n   165→2. No stdout size limit from external processes (item 7) -- could cause OOM\\n   166→3. Agent name from filename not validated (item 5) -- low risk but easy fix\\n   167→4. Discovery latency on every git hook invocation (item 13) -- may impact user experience\\n   168→\\n   169→**Estimated effort to address feedback:**\\n   170→- Critical + Important fixes: ~2-3 hours\\n   171→- Suggestions: ~1-2 hours (optional, can be follow-up)\\n   172→\\n   173→All tests pass. The code is well-organized and follows the project's conventions.\\n   174→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"51baf0d9-cd14-4c5e-87ba-2b913bab8097\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-05T08:36:55.721Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/nodo/work/cli/docs/requirements/external-plugins/review-01.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 01\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-03-04\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\nNo previous reviews.\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n1. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:211] Unbounded `io.ReadAll` on stdin in `ParseHookEvent`**\\n\\n   `ParseHookEvent` calls `io.ReadAll(stdin)` without any size limit. Since external plugins receive data from agent hooks (which may include arbitrary payloads), a malformed or malicious input stream could cause OOM. This is especially important because `ParseHookEvent` is called during git hook execution, where the CLI acts as a gatekeeper.\\n\\n   Suggested fix: Use `io.LimitReader(stdin, maxParseHookBytes)` with a reasonable limit (e.g., 10MB).\\n\\n   ```go\\n   const maxParseHookBytes = 10 * 1024 * 1024\\n   data, err := io.ReadAll(io.LimitReader(stdin, maxParseHookBytes))\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:97-98] `ReadTranscript` passes `sessionRef` as a CLI argument without validation**\\n\\n   The `sessionRef` value originates from session metadata and is passed as `--session-ref` to the external binary. In the test agent (`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire-agent-test/main.go`:167), this is used directly as a file path in `os.ReadFile(*sessionRef)`. While the CLI itself is not performing the file read, it is passing potentially attacker-controlled strings to an external process as arguments.\\n\\n   This is less of a concern than it might appear because:\\n   - The external binary is trusted (found on PATH, user opted in via `external_agents: true`)\\n   - The CLI is not interpreting the value, just forwarding it\\n\\n   However, the `sessionRef` and similar path parameters (`--path`, `--session-dir`, `--subagents-dir`) are passed as CLI arguments that could contain shell metacharacters. Since `exec.CommandContext` does NOT invoke a shell, this is safe from shell injection. **No action required** -- documenting this for the record.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n3. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:97-98, 118, 128, 140, 152, 169, 193, 272, 284, 297, 310, 334, 363, 373, 386] Many methods use `context.Background()` instead of accepting a context parameter**\\n\\n   Fifteen methods create a fresh `context.Background()` instead of propagating a caller-supplied context. This means:\\n   - The 30-second default timeout from `run()` is the only safeguard\\n   - Callers cannot cancel these operations (e.g., during graceful shutdown)\\n   - Operations triggered during git hooks (which have tight time budgets) cannot enforce their own deadlines\\n\\n   The `agent.Agent` interface methods like `ReadTranscript`, `GetSessionID`, `ResolveSessionFile`, `FormatResumeCommand`, etc. do not accept a context, so fixing this would require interface changes. At minimum, consider:\\n   - Filing a follow-up issue to add context to the agent interface\\n   - Adding a comment explaining why `context.Background()` is used (interface limitation)\\n\\n4. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/hooks_cmd.go`:31-32] Discovery timeout context is cancelled immediately after `DiscoverAndRegister` returns, but the context was already used synchronously**\\n\\n   The code is:\\n   ```go\\n   discoveryCtx, discoveryCancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 5*time.Second)\\n   defer discoveryCancel()\\n   external.DiscoverAndRegister(discoveryCtx)\\n   ```\\n\\n   The `defer discoveryCancel()` fires when `newHooksCmd()` returns. Since `DiscoverAndRegister` is synchronous, this works correctly. However, there is a subtle issue: the 5-second timeout is for ALL discovery combined. If there are many `entire-agent-*` binaries on PATH, each `New()` call gets a share of this budget, but a single slow binary could consume most of it, starving later ones. The `New()` call inherits the discovery context deadline, so slow binaries will eventually timeout, but the remaining budget for subsequent binaries shrinks.\\n\\n   This is acceptable for now but worth documenting. Consider logging the remaining budget when starting each binary probe during discovery.\\n\\n5. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/discovery.go`:55-56] Agent name from filename is used without sanitization**\\n\\n   The agent name is derived from the binary filename:\\n   ```go\\n   agentName := types.AgentName(strings.TrimPrefix(name, binaryPrefix))\\n   ```\\n\\n   If a binary is named `entire-agent-../../etc/shadow`, the resulting agent name would be `../../etc/shadow`. While this does not cause path traversal (the name is used as a registry key, not a file path), it could cause confusion in logs and display. Consider validating the agent name contains only `[a-z0-9-]` characters.\\n\\n   Suggested fix:\\n   ```go\\n   agentName := strings.TrimPrefix(name, binaryPrefix)\\n   if !regexp.MustCompile(`^[a-z0-9][a-z0-9-]*$`).MatchString(agentName) {\\n       logging.Debug(ctx, \\\"skipping external agent (invalid name)\\\", slog.String(\\\"binary\\\", name))\\n       continue\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n6. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:415-416] `cmd.Environ()` inherits the full parent environment**\\n\\n   The external binary receives the entire environment of the CLI process. This includes potentially sensitive variables (API keys, tokens, etc.). Consider using a minimal environment instead, or at least documenting this as a security consideration in the protocol docs.\\n\\n   At minimum, the protocol documentation should state that external agents receive the parent process environment, so plugin authors are aware they should not leak env vars.\\n\\n7. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:427] No limit on stdout buffer size**\\n\\n   `cmd.Stdout = &stdoutBuf` collects the entire stdout of the external binary into memory. A malicious or buggy external agent could write gigabytes to stdout, causing OOM. Consider wrapping the buffer with a `LimitedWriter` or checking the size after the process exits.\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n8. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external_test.go`:36-101] Test mock scripts use shell string interpolation for JSON**\\n\\n   The `mockInfoScript` function builds shell scripts by string-concatenating JSON:\\n   ```go\\n   return `#!/bin/sh\\n   case \\\"$1\\\" in\\n     info)\\n       echo '` + infoJSON + `'\\n   ```\\n\\n   If `infoJSON` contains single quotes, this will break the shell script. The current tests are safe because the JSON values are controlled, but this is fragile. Consider using a heredoc or writing the JSON to a separate file that the script reads.\\n\\n9. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/capabilities.go`] `wrappedAgent` duplicates every method signature from `Agent`**\\n\\n   The `wrappedAgent` is a thin delegation layer with ~80 lines of boilerplate. This is a reasonable approach in Go (no built-in delegation), but consider adding a comment at the top of the struct explaining why all methods are forwarded rather than using embedding (embedding would expose the underlying `*Agent` directly and bypass capability gating).\\n\\n10. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/discovery.go`:22-93] `DiscoverAndRegister` has no way to report partial failures to callers**\\n\\n    All errors during discovery are logged and swallowed. The function returns nothing. This is fine for the current fire-and-forget usage, but if callers ever need to know which agents failed and why (e.g., for `entire status` diagnostics), the function signature would need to change.\\n\\n    Consider returning a `[]DiscoveryError` or similar for future extensibility, even if current callers ignore it.\\n\\n11. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/types.go`:148-172] `eventJSON.toEvent()` uses unchecked integer cast for `EventType`**\\n\\n    ```go\\n    ev := &agent.Event{\\n        Type: agent.EventType(ej.Type),\\n    ```\\n\\n    The `ej.Type` integer is directly cast to `agent.EventType` without validating it is a known event type. An external agent returning an unknown event type (e.g., `999`) would propagate through the system. Consider validating the type against known values.\\n\\n12. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/external/external.go`:123-137] `GetSessionID` silently returns empty string on any error**\\n\\n    Three different error paths (marshal, run, unmarshal) all return `\\\"\\\"`. This matches the interface contract (built-in agents also return `\\\"\\\"` on failure), but makes debugging difficult. Consider adding debug logging for these failures:\\n\\n    ```go\\n    func (e *Agent) GetSessionID(input *agent.HookInput) string {\\n        data, err := marshalHookInput(input)\\n        if err != nil {\\n            logging.Debug(context.Background(), \\\"GetSessionID marshal failed\\\", slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()))\\n            return \\\"\\\"\\n        }\\n        // ...\\n    }\\n    ```\\n\\n13. **[`/Users/nodo/work/cli/cmd/entire/cli/hooks_cmd.go`:31-33] Discovery runs on every `entire hooks` invocation**\\n\\n    `DiscoverAndRegister` scans PATH and calls `info` on every matching binary, which happens on every git hook invocation (commit, push, etc.). This adds latency to every git operation. The 5-second timeout bounds worst case, but even the happy path involves filesystem scanning + process spawning for each plugin.\\n\\n    Consider caching discovery results (e.g., in a temp file with a short TTL) to avoid re-scanning on every hook call. This is especially important because git hooks are latency-sensitive.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- **Capability gating pattern (`capabilities.go`)**: The `CapabilityDeclarer` + `As*` helper pattern is elegant. It allows external agents to implement all interfaces (through the `wrappedAgent`) while only exposing declared capabilities, AND it preserves backward compatibility with built-in agents that use direct type assertions. This is a well-thought-out design.\\n\\n- **Thorough test coverage**: The test suite covers happy paths, error cases, deduplication, name conflicts, non-executable files, directories, disabled settings, empty PATH, unreadable directories, and info failures. The capability gating tests cover all combinations of declared/undeclared capabilities for every optional interface.\\n\\n- **Security-conscious defaults**: The feature flag (`external_agents: false` by default), the 5-second discovery timeout, the 30-second per-call timeout, and the `WaitDelay` on subprocesses all show good defensive thinking.\\n\\n- **Clean refactoring**: The migration from direct type assertions (`ag.(agent.HookSupport)`) to the capability-aware helpers (`agent.AsHookSupport(ag)`) across the codebase is thorough and consistent, touching all 15+ call sites without missing any.\\n\\n- **Protocol versioning**: Including `protocol_version` in the `info` response and checking it upfront prevents subtle compatibility issues as the protocol evolves.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n\\nThe architecture is sound and the implementation is well-structured. The capability gating pattern is particularly nice. However, there are security concerns that should be addressed before merging since this feature executes untrusted external binaries:\\n\\n**Key concerns:**\\n1. Unbounded `io.ReadAll` in `ParseHookEvent` (item 1) -- a straightforward fix\\n2. No stdout size limit from external processes (item 7) -- could cause OOM\\n3. Agent name from filename not validated (item 5) -- low risk but easy fix\\n4. Discovery latency on every git hook invocation (item 13) -- may impact user experience\\n\\n**Estimated effort to address feedback:**\\n- Critical + Important fixes: ~2-3 hours\\n- Suggestions: ~1-2 hours (optional, can be follow-up)\\n\\nAll tests pass. The code is well-organized and follows the project's conventions.\\n\",\"numLines\":174,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":174}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"2bd0bd85-3be4-47b8-9020-58c67be011cb\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"51baf0d9-cd14-4c5e-87ba-2b913bab8097\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/nodo/work/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"9dfe422d-4252-4113-aeb0-edbfac2dec29\",\"version\":\"2.1.68\",\"gitBranch\":\"nodo/external-plugins\",\"slug\":\"cozy-churning-pie\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01DV86FsLNGMMtK9NfTUjHWJ\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The first critical issue is unbounded `io.ReadAll` on stdin in `Par